0","1455–Female":"1455–Zesnulá","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","about 1438":"okolo 1438","about 1445":"okolo 1445","1460":"1460","about 1460":"okolo 1460","1438":"1438","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, Anglie","Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England":"Wythenshawe, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1438–about 1460":"omkring 1438–omkring 1460","1435–Male":"1435–Afdød","1413–Female":"1413–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1455–Female":"1455–Afdød","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","about 1438":"omkring 1438","about 1445":"omkring 1445","1460":"1460","about 1460":"omkring 1460","1438":"1438","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, England","Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England":"Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1438–about 1460":"circa 1438–circa 1460","1435–Male":"1435–Overleden","1413–Female":"1413–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1455–Female":"1455–Overleden","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","about 1438":"circa 1438","about 1445":"circa 1445","1460":"1460","about 1460":"circa 1460","1438":"1438","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, England","Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England":"Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"about 1438–about 1460":"about 1438–about 1460","1435–Male":"1435–Deceased","1413–Female":"1413–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1455–Female":"1455–Deceased","1438–1460":"1438–1460","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","about 1438":"about 1438","about 1445":"about 1445","1460":"1460","about 1460":"about 1460","1438":"1438","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, England","Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England":"Wythenshawe, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>bold</i> ‘dwelling-house’ (Old English <i>bold</i> the West Midland and northwestern form of Old English <i>bōthl</i>, <i>bōtl</i>), especially in the sense ‘castle or manor house’ for someone who lived or worked at the main house, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, for example Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Bollmann","meanings":["German:","elaborated derivative of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i> (see   Bold   4).","topographic name for a man who lived on a rounded hill, from Middle Low German <i>bol</i> ‘rounded hill’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, or a habitational name for someone from any of several places called Boll (see   Boll  ). Compare   Bolman  ."]},{"name":"Bowlds","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Bold  ."]},{"name":"Boldman","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Boldemann</b>: from a compound of a variant of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i> (see   Bold   4) + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Bodle","meanings":["English: habitational name from Buddle Oak in Halse (Somerset), Buddle in Fordingbridge (Hampshire), Buddle in Niton (Isle of Wight), Budleigh in Moretonhampstead (Devon), or Budle in Bamburgh (Northumberland), all named from Middle English <i>bothel</i>, Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’, probably denoting a homestead of some considerable size. See also   Bold  .","English (West Midlands): variant of   Beadle  ."]},{"name":"Bolds","meanings":["English: variant of   Bold  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Boldt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hermann, Kurt, Bernhard, Dieter, Egon, Gerd, Gerhard, Gunter, Gunther, Heinz, Hilde.","German and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold’. See also German   Bold  , compare   Bolt  ."]},{"name":"Bolda","meanings":["Polish: from the German personal name <i>Bold</i> (see   Bold   4).","Hungarian: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Boldizsár</i>, Hungarian form of   Baltazar  ."]},{"name":"Bolt","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bolt</i> ‘bolt, bar’, also ‘bundle’ (Old English <i>bolt</i> ‘arrow’). One of the most common senses of this word was ‘the blunt-headed bolt of a crossbow’, so it could have been given to an archer or to a maker of iron bars or bolts. <i>Bolt</i> was also used metaphorically for a short, thickset, or tubby person and for someone who was physically <i>upright as a bolt</i>, i.e. ‘as straight as an arrow’.","English: variant of   Bold   1.","Dutch, North German, and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold’. See also German   Bold  , compare German and Danish   Boldt  ."]},{"name":"Bolton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in northern England named Bolton (Lancashire, Northumberland, Westmorland, and Yorkshire) or from Boulton in Derbyshire and East Lothian in Scotland, from Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."]},{"name":"Bolding","meanings":["German: patronymic from   Bold   as a personal name.","Danish: habitational name from a place so named in Jutland.","English (Middlesex): variant of   Balding   1."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Bold was born about 1438, in Coddington, Cheshire, England. She had at least 2 daughters with Hugh Massey. She died about 1460, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 24."},"et":{"about 1438–about 1460":"umbes 1438–umbes 1460","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1413–Female":"1413–Surnud","–M